Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Gurnelius Terer¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. It icludes data such as the duration of the ride, starting time, end time, station name, gender, and other valuable data.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 174952 observations in the dataset with 16 features with the following datatypes:

  • Object: start_station_name, end_station_name, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip
  • Float: start_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude and member_birth_year
  • Int: duration_sec and bike_id
  • Categorical: user_type

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I most interested in the features that are suitable for predicting the duration of a trip.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe that the user type will be a strong factor in determining the length of a ride. I also believe that the start time and age will be cotributing factors.

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start by looking at the distribution of the ride duration (duration_sec):

In [16]:
def plot_hist(x, bins, xlim,title, xlabel, ylabel="Frequency"):
    '''
    Plots a histogram
    
    Parameter:
    x : x variable
    bins = constom bins to use for the plot
    xlim: Limit values for x variables
    title: title of the plot
    xlabel: x-axis label 
    ylabel: y-axis label (Optional)
    '''
    
    plt.hist(data=df, x =x, bins = bins)
    plt.xlim(xlim)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)

sns.countplot()
bins = np.arange(0, df["duration_sec"].max()+100, 100)
plot_hist("duration_sec", bins, (0,3000), "Distribution of Ride Duration", "Duration [Sec]" );

The distribution is skewed to the right. Let's try to transform the data and plot again.

In [17]:
log_binsize = 0.1
bins = 10 ** np.arange(1.7,  np.log10(df['duration_sec']).max() + log_binsize, log_binsize)
ticks =  [100, 300, 1000, 3000, 10000, 30000, 100000]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
plt.xlim(0, 10000)
plt.xlabel('Trip Duration (sec)')

# Function for plotting bar charts
def plot_bar(data, xlabel, ylabel, title, kind='bar'):
    '''
    Plots a bar chart
    
    Parameter:
    data: Pandas DataFrame/ Series
    xlabel: x-axis label 
    ylabel: y-axis label (Optional)
    title: title of the plot
    '''
    
    data.plot(kind=kind)
    
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.style.use("seaborn")

    .value_counts() # Total counts for each hour
    .sort_index() # Sort by hour

def plot_line(df, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    '''
    Plots a line graph
    
    Parameter:
    df: Pandas DataFrame/ Series
    xlabel: x-axis label 
    ylabel: y-axis label (Optional)
    title: title of the plot
    '''
    df.plot(kind="line")
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    

plot_line(df_duration, "Hour", "Number of Rides", "Number of Rides Vs Hour")

The number of rides peak at 7 a.m in the morning and repeats at 5 p.m in the evening. This may possibly indicates that most users use the rideshare service to get to work in the morning and to return home in the evening.

Conclusions¶

After a thorough exploration of the dataset, the following conclusions are arrived at:

  1. The number of rides peak at 7 a.m in the morning and repeats at 5 p.m in the evening.This may possibly indicate that most users use the rideshare service to get to work in the morning and to return home in the evening.

  2. Users take longer rides on Weekends as compared to weekdays.

  3. Customers take the longest rides for all genders and during any day compared tp subscribers.

  4. The longest rides in the day are taken at 3 a.m. This is true for both customers and subscribers. It is also concluded that, generally, customers take the longest rides at any hour of the day as compared to subscribers.
